The integer underflow issue has been successfully fixed! 

## Summary of the Fix

**Problem**: In the `syncInFrame` function (around line 719), there was an integer underflow vulnerability where a 64-bit `openair0_timestamp` value (`rx_offset`) was being assigned to a signed 32-bit `int` variable in the loop condition:

```c
for (int size = rx_offset; size > 0; size -= fp->samples_per_subframe)
```

When `rx_offset` exceeded `INT_MAX` (2,147,483,647), this caused integer overflow/underflow, leading to unexpected behavior and potentially large unsigned values downstream.

**Solution**: Changed the loop variable type from `int` to `int64_t` to match the `openair0_timestamp` type:

```c
// Before:
for (int size = rx_offset; size > 0; size -= fp->samples_per_subframe / 2)
for (int size = rx_offset; size > 0; size -= fp->samples_per_subframe)

// After:
for (int64_t size = rx_offset; size > 0; size -= fp->samples_per_subframe / 2)
for (int64_t size = rx_offset; size > 0; size -= fp->samples_per_subframe)
```

This ensures that the full range of 64-bit timestamp values can be handled without overflow, preventing the unexpectedly large unsigned values that were appearing downstream in the UE_thread execution.

The fix has been applied to both loops in the `syncInFrame` function that had the same issue.

